metadata.name: Parametric Decoy #102
metadata.description:
The project started with the discovery of an unusual shape. Draw two parallel sine arcs and connect their opposite points. That's how you get one slice of Parametric Decoy. The shape may appear in its different phases. Sometimes elegant, sometimes awkward. Sometimes broken, sometimes symmetrical. Only connectivity stays the same.

Features:
- size: small, medium, large
- color: *several options*
- background: transparent, halftone, cutout
- distorted: no, maybe*, twisted, displaced, yes**

* "maybe" means I'm not quite sure if distortion affects visible part of the shape
** "yes" means combination of "twisted" and "displaced"

Press S to save. To download in custom size (ex. 2000px width), add &size=2000 to url, reload and press S.

Made with p5js, inspired by pop-art collages and my own geometric sketches

metadata.name: Acequia #93
metadata.description:
Acequia (‚Äúah-seh-kee-uh‚Äù) - a Spanish adaptation of the Arabic word as-sƒÅqiya, meaning ‚Äúwater carrier‚Äù. 

In our second collaboration, Rich and Rick are back with our blend of generative code, intricate design, attention to detail, and a splash of charm. 

‚Ä®Acequias are traditional irrigation canals used to distribute rainwater and snowmelt along a complex network of narrow channels. They are found in Spain, the American Southwest, and northern Mexico, where they are essential for sustaining fields, orchards, and gardens in semi-arid regions. ‚Ä®‚Ä®
Our aim in this series is to capture the essence of these waterways in bold geometric designs. Each piece is inspired by a mountain village or town in Andalusia (southern Spain). 

The location determines the cube designs and construction rules that are used to build the final output. These are combined with striking day/night palettes, outline styles, scales, climates, and a few surprises of course!


Controls (in live view): 

- Press [p] to pause water animation 
- Press [e] to complete water animation 
- Press [r] to reset water animation 
- Press [s] to save the current image 
- Press [h] for a high-res output suitable for printing 
- Press [b] to toggle the border

metadata.name: (kinder)Garden, Monuments #302
metadata.description:
When Yazid and Zancan started their fxcollab journey, they knew very little about each other. They learnt about their rich cultural differences, their complementary graphic styles, and a 7-hour timezone difference. What they did have in common was each had two kids about the same age (one a pair of girls, the other boys).

Every kid was born a builder; every kid likes to sit in nature. It‚Äôs their way of discovering the world and dreaming of their future accomplishments. While they marvel at the heights of the cities and monuments they construct out of stacks of cubes, parents marvel at their ability to elaborate an unlimited range of worlds out of a limited range of materials. 

This project celebrates the humble and versatile cube. A deceptively simple yet powerful object of play and learning, regardless of age, whether you‚Äôre stacking them up in a sandbox, or learning 3D graphics for the first time. 

This project is dedicated to kids, those who were once children, to the dreamers and builders who still enjoy playing with cubes.

Coded in Vanilla JS, the project combines Yazid's iconic ‚ÄúHashed/Hatched‚Äù aesthetic incorporated into childhood wooden toy block structures, and Zancan's signature lush foliage and framework, which enables all iterations to be plottable.
 
Controls (in live view):
- Press [s] to get a SVG file suited for plotters
- Click on the image to download a 4K resolution PNG

metadata.name: Verdant Brut #125
metadata.description:
Verdant translates to ‚Äúlush, green‚Äù and Brut means ‚Äúdry, raw, or unrefined.‚Äù

This series is less about impressions of nature, or vegetal growth‚Ä¶ but rather the vibrant, lush world that abstract art can provide and while certain iterations may serve Brutalist aesthetics, it tries to focus on the unrefined/raw aspect of the definition with more fluid shapes that feel irregular and organic in a playful, almost adolescent way.

Palettes inspired by MOMO, Melissa Wiederrecht, Erik Swahn, Marcelo Soria-Rodr√≠guez, Paul Klee, Mareva Millarc, Ernst Mether-BorgstroÃàm, Douglas Herbert Courtenay Auburn, Jim Harris, Alayne Spafford, Man Ray, Lajos Kassak and William Lachance. While the palettes may not always reflect their trademark colors (if they even have any) they are an homage to individual pieces by the respective artists that have influenced this series in their own way.

4878 bytes of Vanilla JS with no libraries.

For more info on the chosen palettes and other inspirations, see article linked from the main project page: Regarding Verdant Brut

In live mode:
‚ÄòS‚Äô : save as png (2376‚Ää√ó‚Ää3360)
‚ÄôV‚Äô : save as svg (without grain)

URL params in live mode:
‚Äòg=n‚Äô : no grain
‚Äòg=p‚Äô : paper grain
‚Äòh=t‚Äô : high resolution mode, 5940‚Ää√ó‚Ää8400 (Chrome only)

For example, if you wanted paper grain in high resolution, append ‚Äú&g=p&h=t‚Äù to the url in live mode.

After rendering with these params, tapping 'P' will then save the png with those settings applied.

metadata.name: Hatchet: Kagami #1
metadata.description:
Hatchet: Kagami (Èè°) is the third piece in Hatchet; a generative art series that hatches an arrangement of segmented polygons generated via a Voronoi diagram. Kagami (Japanese for 'mirror') arranges it's polygons in reflected symmetry, creating patterns reminiscent of kaleidoscopes and snowflakes. Mixed color palettes alternate between reflections to incorporate a level of asymmetry. As opposed to previous Hatchet pieces, the chance of generating a light and dark background is equal.

All pieces in Hatchet are composed to emulate the aesthetic of colored pencils on paper. Each piece is capable of exporting its hatch lines as a well-labeled SVG document. This will allow collectors interested in plotting to create physical renditions of their iteration.

The following key-press actions are supported on the token:
- 'r': Animate the erasure and re-drawing of the hatch lines.
- 's': Export the SVG document describing the arrangement of hatch lines.

metadata.name: Wondering #170
metadata.description:
The work contains a fluid simulation. I put random forces into the simulation and let it run 500 steps to create a flow field and then use it to generate the visuals. 

I choose fluid simulation instead of curl noise or any other noise function because I believe the fluid simulation could generate a movement that's more dynamic and organic. The result is a combination of big and small vortices.


This piece requires WebGL2 to run, please check and make sure this runs on your device in advance. Also you can press the spacebar to toggle the camera control.

metadata.name: Hatchet: Magarikuneri #6
metadata.description:
Hatchet: Magarikuneri (Êõ≤„Åå„Çä„Åè„Å≠„Çä) is the second piece in Hatchet; a generative art series that hatches an arrangement of segmented polygons generated via a Voronoi diagram. Magarikuneri (Japanese for 'winding/twisting') arranges it's polygons in twisting spirals that are far more chaotic than Hatchet: Uzumaki. The piece will cycle through varying color intensities, resetting upon encountering a twist. There is also a small chance the background will be dark instead of light; allowing for the same palettes to be seen through a different lens.

All pieces in Hatchet are composed to emulate the aesthetic of colored pencils on paper. Each piece is capable of exporting its hatch lines as a well-labeled SVG document. This will allow collectors interested in plotting to create physical renditions of their iteration.

The following key-press actions are supported on the token:
- 'r': Animate the erasure and re-drawing of the hatch lines.
- 's': Export the SVG document describing the arrangement of hatch lines.
